🚨Trauma Thursday🚨🖐
⚠️Viewer discretion advised⚠️

Which of the following do you think caused this finger injury?
.
1. Hand slipped into a malfunctioning conveyor belt at a supermarket and became stuck
2. Bitten by a snapping turtle when trying to move it out of the road
3. Bitten by a horse when trying to feed it 
4. Bitten by a chihuahua 
5. Truck door slammed shut on hand
6. Wedding ring caught on a metal fence when trying to climb over it 
.
Tell us your guess👇
.
(The correct answer might surprise you! Will be posted tomorrow)

node.text:
Large flatworm in a man’s intestine!! 🪱
.
A 40-year-old man presented to the emergency department with fatigue that had progressively worsened over a period of 3 months. 
He had recently emigrated from Mexico, where he had worked on a farm and eaten unwashed vegetables there. 
.
Patient examination revealed pallor of the oral mucosa, and labs showed severe anemia. 
.
Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography was performed, and large flatworms were visualized in the intestines (shown in video).

Worms were extracted and identified as the common liver fluke, Fasciola hepatica. Fasciola eggs in the feces of host animals (commonly sheep) contaminate fresh water; the larvae mature in snails and attach to vegetation. After the parasites are ingested by humans, they penetrate the intestine and invade the hepatobiliary tree.
.
The patient was treated with a blood transfusion and the medication triclabendazole. Trilabendazole is used to treat infections caused by flat worms. It is in a class of medications called anthelmintics. It works by killing the flat worms.
.
Within 1 month of treatment at the hospital, the patient made a full recovery. 
Credit to @medicaltalks

node.text:
During the American Civil War, serious attempts were made to reconstruct the faces of soldiers injured in battle.
Repost from: @drlindseyfitzharris 
. 
Photos 1 & 2: 
Pictured here is Private Roland Ward, who underwent several operations WITHOUT anesthetic to repair his face in the 1860s! 
.
Photos 3 & 4: 
The most skillful surgeon to emerge during this period was Gurdon Buck, who helped repair the face of Private Carleton Burgan after a gangrenous infection destroyed his upper mouth, palate, right cheek & eye. With the help of a dentist named Thomas B. Gunning, Buck was able to reconstruct parts of Burgan’s face using rudimentary skin grafts and flap techniques shown in photo 4. 
.
Photo 5: 
Buck was one of only a handful of surgeons willing to attempt such risky procedures as infection rates during this period were staggering. Most soldiers were left with terrible wounds, gaps, and missing tissue in their faces. When Private Joseph Harvey was hit by a shell fragment, he found employment as a night watchman, and died a few years later.
.
.
Images credit: National Museum of Civil War Medicine and National Museum of Health & Medicine.

node.text:
⚠️Intraocular foreign body⚠️👁
This case involves a malfunctioning piece of machinery that shot a metal washer into a workers eye. Unfortunately he was not wearing any eye protection or safety glasses at the time of the incident. 
.
Luckily the man was taken to a hospital and the foreign body was safely removed. He did not have any long term effects or vision loss. 
.
Even though this man was extremely lucky to have no lasting damage, vision loss and eye injury are very common with Intraocular injuries. 
.
Always remember to protect your eyes wear safety glasses! 👓
